What happens when you get to the checkout and the price sticker on the shelf says one price but when the cashier rings it up it's a price that is a lot higher. The cashier says that was last week's sale price and the sticker on the shelf hasn't been changed yet. I had to leave the item with the cashier because I didn't want to pay the higher price.

Unfortunately, there is no federal law that governs scanner price accuracy. However, many retailers uphold the Scanner Price Accuracy Voluntary Code which is endorsed by the Competition Bureau of Canada. The code includes the Item Free Scanner Policy which stipulates: if an item scanned at checkout is a higher price than advertised by the store or displayed in the store, the lower price will be honoured. Also, if the correct price of the product is $10 or less, the retailer will give the product to the customer free of charge; or, if the product is over $10, the retailer will give a discount of $10 off the correct price. The next time this happens to you, ask if the retailer upholds the code. You can learn more about the Scanner Price Accuracy Voluntary Code here: [[SHARE]]
